data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`). Here's the full migration:

## Problem

| Removed API | Why it fails on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`), no-ops |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, this **won't interrupt** CPU-bound work that ignores the token. If `work` is a tight loop, it must check a `CancellationToken` internally. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` ≠ killing the work** | When the timeout fires, `WaitAsync` throws but the underlying task keeps running (fire-and-forget). The old `Thread.Abort` truly stopped the thread. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **Blocking call interruption** | If `work` calls `Thread.Sleep(ms)`, that won't be interrupted. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. |

## For truly uncooperative code

If `work` runs code you **cannot modify** (e.g., third-party library with no cancellation support), the only safe .NET 8 equivalent of `Thread.Abort` is process isolation:

```csharp
// Move uncooperative work to a child process and use Process.Kill()
var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

**Bottom line:** The paradigm shift is from *preemptive* (runtime injects exception) to *cooperative* (code checks token). For the cooperative model to work, pass `CancellationToken` through the entire call chain and check it at regular intervals inside `work`.
